1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:18,640
Crawl back with you for chapter 2. There is a unique kind of dread when you see your car crushed. To even prepare for this moment, your insurer needs your car's exact details upfront: the year, make, model, and its estimated present value.

2
00:00:18,640 --> 00:00:55,680
Under section three, your policy covers loss or damage. This covers collisions, fires, overturning, theft, and malicious acts. If your car is immobilized, the policy even covers the towing fee to the nearest repair shop. However, it does not cover everything. You cannot claim everyday wear and tear, mechanical breakdowns, damage limited strictly to your tires, or malicious damage caused by your own family members. When it is time for repairs, insurers use an authorized repair limit, meaning costs are capped at the manufacturer's price catalog.

3
00:00:55,680 --> 00:01:25,200
You will also share the burden of the repair costs first through depreciation. Because a car loses value over time, if your older car needs brand new replacement parts, you will pay a percentage of that parts cost. Second, you pay a deductible. This is a set minimum amount you pay out of pocket, which keeps the system free of tiny nuisance claims so premiums stay affordable for everyone.

4
00:01:25,200 --> 00:01:56,479
But what if the crash is catastrophic? If the damage you cause ruins another person's property or leaves them with life-altering injuries, the basic limits will not be enough. Section four, excess liability insurance acts as your ultimate safety net, paying the massive sums that go beyond the limits of the first two sections. Now that we understand what is covered, we need to talk about the rules that hold this entire system together.